@Cosmic | Desearch [τ, χ)  @Professor | Desearch  I wanted to suggest an improvement on the validator side on the max_execution_time cutoff. 

Right now after the 10s limit (for example) there is a hard timeout which leads to the results being discarded (even if they are mid stream) and not scored. This leads to situation where even if the summary has started to stream to the validator and is in the middle of providing the information the results are discarded. 

I would like to propose a system where instead of just discarding and socring with 0 you have a overflow period (lets say 5s) and apply an exponential penalty if the miner extends into this 5s limit starting with 0% penalty up to 100% penalty if they go over the 5s. 

This way exerience will be better for the user as well in case sometimes the results take a few ms or a second longer (this can be for alot of reasons like network latency sometimes) as they still get their result and also incentivises miners to actually stream responses and have a more open ended finish to their response (right now everything has to be very very measured especially at the 10s limit)

Created task for it

Hey @Sheik , really appreciate you taking the time to share this — it’s the kind of feedback that actually helps us improve.

Right now, Desearch uses a five-layer scoring mechanism to evaluate miner responses:
    1.    Web content relevance – checks if links are accurate, on-topic, and hallucination-free.
    2.    X (Twitter) content relevance – filters out noisy or unrelated posts.
    3.    AI summary quality – ensures summaries reflect the actual source, not just generic LLM output.
    4.    Response performance – measures miner response speed and completeness.
    5.    Penalty logic – flags AI-generated or low-quality responses.

But we hear you — it’s not always consistent. That’s why we’re working on a major upgrade to the scoring system this month, focused on improving data quality checks and aligning incentives better.

We’ve also started collecting real-world cases from users to guide this update. If you have any queries where Desearch got things wrong or felt off, feel free to share — it would help a lot.

We’re also planning to launch a new benchmark with a large query set once the updated scoring is live.

Also curious to hear your thoughts on Deep Research — it’s our newer mode focused on multi-step queries. And more search modes (like people search, company search, etc.) are in the works.
